<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Metromedia Co. Chairman John Werner Kluge is
worth an estimated $5.2 billion, but he had to back into first
place on Forbes magazine's annual list of the 400 richest Americans.
   Kluge displaced Sam Walton, head of the Wal-Mart stores discount
chain, who divvied his $9 billion fortune among himself and his
four children and ended a four-year reign as Forbes's wealthiest
person.
   Overall, Forbes' richest, announced Monday, are worth an
estimated total of $269 billion, up nearly $50 billion from the
previous year, a 22 percent increase that substantially outpaced
last year's 4.4 percent inflation rate.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jaguar PLC is in talks with General Motors Corp.
about a possible cooperative operating agreement, setting the stage
for a possible tug-of-war between GM and Ford Motor Co. over the
British automaker.
   Jaguar said Monday that GM was considering buying a minority
stake in Jaguar as part of such an arrangement. Ford announced
three weeks ago it wanted to buy up to 15 percent of Jaguar, and
left open the option of making a full bid for the British company.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Representatives from MGM-UA
Communications Co. and Australia's Qintex Group are continuing
discussions in an attempt to get Qintex's stalled $1.5 billion
takeover bid for MGM-UA back on track.
   The deal was placed in jeopardy last week when MGM-UA revealed
that Qintex failed to make a scheduled $50 million down payment.
The two sides met Monday. Qintex last month outbid media mogul
Rupert Murdoch for MGM-UA by $100 million.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Striking Boeing Co. machinists met with 25 other
labor unions in a bid for support as their six-day walkout against
the jetliner manufacturer dragged on with no signs of new contract
talks.
   Tom Baker, president of the International Association of
Machinists and Aerospace Workers, Local 751, said Monday the union
wanted to ask for help in case the strike was not quickly resolved.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal HUD officials approved $35 million in
loans on the last day of fiscal 1988 in an apparent rush to spend
the money before it was transferred to another program, according
to auditors and agency documents.
   Most of the Section 312 multifamily housing loans were approved
despite incomplete applications or processing, according to
auditors who alerted the department's general counsel to the
questionable loans. The auditors were told the government was
legally bound to fund nearly all of them.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   USAir Group Inc. stock climbed in heavy
trading after a published report said a major stockholder,
Steinhardt Partners, was buying more shares and looking into other
options aimed at raising the company's stock price.
   Michael H. Steinhardt, a New York money manager whose firm owns
8.3 percent of the Arlington, Va., based airline company, has hired
Wall Street investment banker Wertheim Schroder &amp; Co. to explore
ways to raise the price of the stock, USA Today's Dan Dorfman
reported Monday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   USX Corp. says it has sold all of its equity
interests in South African companies as part of its continuing
restructuring.
   The oil and steel concern Monday withheld the identify of the
buyers and the sale price. USX last week said it was offering to
sell the natural gas and oil reserves of its Texas Oil &amp; Gas Corp.
subsidiary, a move that follows changes in its steel,
transportation and diversified businesses.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A nationwide vote of pilots could be the
proverbial last straw for Eastern Airlines' pilots, who have
entered their eighth month of a bitter strike.
   The Air Line Pilots Association ballot on continuing strike
payments to the Eastern pilots, if negative, would withdraw
financial support from the beleaguered strikers and force them to
pull down their picket lines after numerous setbacks in their fight
against Eastern boss Frank Lorenzo. The votes were to be counted
today.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DEARBORN, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soichiro Honda, the founder of the
Japanese automaker that bears his name, dropped by the Henry Ford
Museum and recalled the day he first saw an automobile _ a Model T
he chased down a Japanese road when he was 6.
   In addition to Monday's museum visit, the 82-year-old Honda was
in the Detroit area to be inducted today into the Automotive Hall
of Fame. Honda was the first Japanese automaker to establish
assembly plants in the United States.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices kept their recent run of record highs going Monday
with a small advance in slow holiday trading. The Dow Jones
industrial average rose 5.89 to 2,791.41, hitting a new closing
high for the fifth consecutive session.
   The dollar turned narrowly mixed in thin holiday trading.
   Corporate bond prices edged higher but trading was very light as
the U.S. market for Treasury issues was closed.
   Grain and soybean futures prices closed lower; cotton prices
were sharply lower; precious metals drifted lower; livestock and
pork futures were mixed; energy futures were higher and coffee
prices continued to drift lower.
</TEXT>
